{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Despite recent advancements, current solutions for the bidirectional control of hand prostheses still have non-trivial limits which reduce the overall usability of dexterous hand prostheses.",
    "Dexterous prostheses are controlled by processing electromyographic (EMG) signals recorded from the residual muscles of the amputee in the stump or elsewhere.",
    "Surface EMG (sEMG) acquisition does not require surgery, so it is largely used in upper-limb prosthetic control 154.",
    "However, despite the accessibility, EMG control provides limited usability in practice due to high degrees of freedom and is further limited when external factors are introduced, such as changes in electrode position or environmental conditions 155.",
    "The most common control approach is based on decoding EMG signals using traditional machine learning approaches (e.g., MLP, SVM) to discriminate users' gestures."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
